            "answer_text": "It is generally agreed that the island of Ithak\u0113, which was said in ancient times to have been the home of the hero Odysseus and which is the main setting for a large part of the Odyssey, is the same island known today in Greek as Ithaki, a rather small island located in the Ionian Sea off the northeast coast of the much larger island of Kefalonia. This identification is widely accepted. It is, however, not entirely uncontroversial. Many scholars have noticed that the geography of the island described in the Odyssey is not entirely consistent with modern-day Ithaki. Most scholars believe this is just because the author of the Odyssey probably lived in Asia Minor and probably never visited Ithak\u0113 himself. Thus, the author makes geographical errors when describing the landscape of an island he had never personally visited. A few scholars, though, have tried to argue that maybe the island known as Ithak\u0113 in Homeric times is not the same island known as Ithaki today. Some people, for instance, have tried to argue that Homer\u2019s Ithak\u0113 is actually part of Kefalonia. Personally, I think that the majority of scholars are probably right and that Ithaki is indeed the best candidate for the island that was reputed in antiquity to have been the home of Odysseus.  ABOVE: Map from Wikimedia Commons showing the location of the Greek island of Ithaki, which is usually identified as the island of Ithak\u0113 in the Odyssey ",
